{"title_page": "Thomas Ferebee", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox military person\n |name         = Thomas Wilson Ferebee\n |image        = Van Kirk Tibbets, and Ferebee.jpg\n |image_size   = 275px\n |caption      = [[Theodore Van Kirk|Van Kirk]], [[Paul Tibbets|Tibbets]], and Thomas Ferebee (right)\n |fun_fact     = [[he has the highest KDR in history at 60,000-80,000]]\n |birth_date   = {{dob|1918|11|09}}\n |death_date   = {{dda|2000|03|16|1918|11|09}}\n |birth_place  = [[Mocksville, North Carolina]], U.S.\n |death_place  = [[Windermere, Florida]], U.S.\n |allegiance   = {{flagu|United States|1960}}\n |branch       = {{air force|United States}}\n |serviceyears = 1942\u20131970\n |rank         = [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n |commands     = \n |unit         = [[509th Composite Group]]\n |battles      = {{ubl|[[World War II]]|[[Vietnam War]]}}\n |awards       = {{ubl|[[Silver Star]]|[[Air Medal]]}}\n |laterwork    = \n}}\n\n'''Thomas Wilson Ferebee''' (November 9, 1918 &ndash; March 16, 2000) was the [[bombardier (air force)|bombardier]] aboard the [[B-29 Superfortress]], ''[[Enola Gay]]'', which dropped the [[atomic bomb]], \"[[Little Boy]]\", on [[Hiroshima]] in 1945.\n\n==Biography==\nThomas Wilson Ferebee was born on a farm outside [[Mocksville, North Carolina]], as the third of eleven children. In 1935, at age 17, he attended [[Lees-McRae College]] in [[Banner Elk, NC]]. Talented in athletics since childhood, he earned awards in [[Track and field|track]], [[basketball]], and [[American football|football]]. After training for a small position with the [[Boston Red Sox]] and not making the team, he joined the [[United States Army|Army]]. A knee injury kept him from service in the [[infantry]] but he was accepted into flight training. After two years of [[flight school]], Ferebee was assigned as a bombardier in the [[European Theater of Operations|European theater]], completing more than 60 bombing missions. In the summer of 1944, he was recruited by [[Colonel]] [[Paul Tibbets]] to be part of the [[509th Composite Group]] which was formed to drop the [[atomic bomb]].\n\nLike Tibbets, Ferebee remained in the military in the years after World War II as the [[U.S. Army Air Forces]] became the [[U.S. Air Force]]. Ferebee spent most of his USAF career in the [[Strategic Air Command]], serving during the [[Cold War]] and in Vietnam. He retired from the U.S. Air Force in December 1970 at [[McCoy AFB]], Florida as a [[Combat Systems Officer|master navigator]] (bombardier) with the rank of [[colonel]]. He then worked as a real estate agent in and around [[Orlando, Florida]]. Like Tibbets, Ferebee never expressed regret for his role in the bombing, saying \"it was a job that had to be done.\"<ref>''Enola Gay'' by Gordon Thomas and Max Morgan Witts, epilogue</ref>\n\nHe died at his home in [[Windermere, Florida]] at the age of 81.<ref>[http://www.mishalov.com/Ferebee.html Thomas Ferebee<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He was survived by his wife, Mary Ann Ferebee, who donated his collection of military documents and objects to the [[North Carolina Museum of History]] in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]].<ref name=\"Salisbury\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.salisburypost.com/breaking/288433096101370.php|title=Ferebee's collection at history museum|accessdate=2008-02-07|publisher=Salisbury Post|date=2007-03-17}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|World War II}}\n* [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki]]\n* [[Kermit Beahan]]\n* [[Ky\u016bj\u014d incident]]\n* [[Surrender of Japan]]\n\n==References==\n[[File:ThomasFerebee.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Picture taken on Tinian after the dropping of [[Little Boy]] on [[Hiroshima]].]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography== \n* [[Fletcher Knebel]] and [[Charles W. Bailey II]] (1960), ''No High Ground'', New York: Harper and Row, {{ISBN|0-313-24221-6}}.\n* [[Gordon Thomas (author)|Gordon Thomas]] and [[Max Morgan Witts]] (1977), ''Enola Gay'', 1978 reprint, New York: Pocket Books, {{ISBN|0-671-81499-0}}.\n\n==External links==\n* {{findagrave|5832883}}\n* [http://alsos.wlu.edu/qsearch.aspx?browse=people/Ferebee,+Thomas Annotated Bibliography for Thomas Ferebee from the Alsos Digital Library for Nuclear Issues]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferebee, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:Lees\u2013McRae College alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki]]\n[[Category:People from Mocksville, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Windermere, Florida]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Star]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force colonels]]\n[[Category:United States Army Air Forces officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Air Forces pilots of World War II]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox military person\n |name         = Thomas Wilson Ferebee\n |image        = Van Kirk Tibbets, and Ferebee.jpg\n |image_size   = 275px\n |caption      = [[Theodore Van Kirk|Van Kirk]], [[Paul Tibbets|Tibbets]], and Thomas Ferebee (right)\n |fun_fact     = [[he has the highest KDR in history at 60,000-80,000]]\n |birth_date   = {{dob|1918|11|09}}\n |death_date   = {{dda|2000|03|16|1918|11|09}}\n |birth_place  = [[Mocksville, North Carolina]], U.S.\n |death_place  = [[Windermere, Florida]], U.S.\n |allegiance   = {{flagu|United States|1960}}\n |branch       = {{air force|United States}}\n |serviceyears = 1942\u20131970\n |rank         = [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n |commands     = \n |unit         = [[509th Composite Group]]\n |battles      = {{ubl|[[World War II]]|[[Vietnam War]]}}\n |awards       = {{ubl|[[Silver Star]]|[[Air Medal]]}}\n |laterwork    = \n}}\n\n'''Thomas Wilson Ferebee''' (November 9, 1918 &ndash; March 16, 2000) was the [[bombardier (air force)|bombardier]] aboard the [[B-29 Superfortress]], ''[[Enola Gay]]'', which dropped the [[atomic bomb]], \"[[Little Boy]]\", on [[Hiroshima]] in 1945.\n\n==Biography==\nThomas Wilson Ferebee was born on a farm outside [[Mocksville, North Carolina]], as the third of eleven children. In 1935, at age 17, he attended [[Lees-McRae College]] in [[Banner Elk, NC]]. Talented in athletics since childhood, he earned awards in [[Track and field|track]], [[basketball]], and [[American football|football]]. After training for a small position with the [[Boston Red Sox]] and not making the team, he joined the [[United States Army|Army]]. A knee injury kept him from service in the [[infantry]] but he was accepted into flight training. After two years of [[flight school]], Ferebee was assigned as a bombardier in the [[European Theater of Operations|European theater]], completing more than 60 bombing missions. In the summer of 1944, he was recruited by [[Colonel]] [[Paul Tibbets]] to be part of the [[509th Composite Group]] which was formed to drop the [[atomic bomb]].\n\nLike Tibbets, Ferebee remained in the military in the years after World War II as the [[U.S. Army Air Forces]] became the [[U.S. Air Force]]. Ferebee spent most of his USAF career in the [[Strategic Air Command]], serving during the [[Cold War]] and in Vietnam. He retired from the U.S. Air Force in December 1970 at [[McCoy AFB]], Florida as a [[Combat Systems Officer|master navigator]] (bombardier) with the rank of [[colonel]]. He then worked as a real estate agent in and around [[Orlando, Florida]]. Like Tibbets, Ferebee never expressed regret for his role in the bombing, saying \"it was a job that had to be done.\"<ref>''Enola Gay'' by Gordon Thomas and Max Morgan Witts, epilogue</ref>\n\nHe died at his home in [[Windermere, Florida]] at the age of 81.<ref>[http://www.mishalov.com/Ferebee.html Thomas Ferebee<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He was survived by his wife, Mary Ann Ferebee, who donated his collection of military documents and objects to the [[North Carolina Museum of History]] in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]].<ref name=\"Salisbury\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.salisburypost.com/breaking/288433096101370.php|title=Ferebee's collection at history museum|accessdate=2008-02-07|publisher=Salisbury Post|date=2007-03-17}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|World War II}}\n* [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki]]\n* [[Kermit Beahan]]\n* [[Ky\u016bj\u014d incident]]\n* [[Surrender of Japan]]\n\n==References==\n[[File:ThomasFerebee.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Picture taken on Tinian after the dropping of [[Little Boy]] on [[Hiroshima]].]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography== \n* [[Fletcher Knebel]] and [[Charles W. Bailey II]] (1960), ''No High Ground'', New York: Harper and Row, {{ISBN|0-313-24221-6}}.\n* [[Gordon Thomas (author)|Gordon Thomas]] and [[Max Morgan Witts]] (1977), ''Enola Gay'', 1978 reprint, New York: Pocket Books, {{ISBN|0-671-81499-0}}.\n\n==External links==\n* {{findagrave|5832883}}\n* [http://alsos.wlu.edu/qsearch.aspx?browse=people/Ferebee,+Thomas Annotated Bibliography for Thomas Ferebee from the Alsos Digital Library for Nuclear Issues]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferebee, Thomas}}\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:Lees\u2013McRae College alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki]]\n[[Category:People from Mocksville, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Windermere, Florida]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Star]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force colonels]]\n[[Category:United States Army Air Forces officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Air Forces pilots of World War II]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Landingdude13", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page":