{"title_page": "Brad Garlinghouse", "text_new": "{{Primary sources|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bradley Kent Garlinghouse\n| image              = Brad_Garlinghouse_-_July_2008.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1971|2|6|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Topeka, Kansas]]\n| residence          = [[Atherton, California]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Kansas]]<br>[[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation         = [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] [[Ripple (company)|Ripple]] (2015-)\n| nationality        = {{Flag icon|United States}}\n}}\n\n'''Bradley Kent''' \"'''Brad'''\" '''Garlinghouse''' (born February 6, 1971, in [[Topeka, Kansas]]) is CEO of financial technology company [[Ripple (company)|Ripple]]. He was formerly the CEO and Chairman of [[Hightail]] (formerly [[YouSendIt]]), the file sharing site.  Prior to Hightail, he was President of Consumer Applications at [[AOL]] for two years, after his role as Senior Vice President at [[Yahoo!]] running its Communications business which included the Homepage, [[Flickr]], [[Yahoo! Mail]], and [[Yahoo! Messenger]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}  While at Yahoo! he penned the famous Peanut Butter Manifesto<ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB116379821933826657 | title = Yahoo Memo: The 'Peanut Butter Manifesto' | work=The Wall Street Journal | date=November 18, 2006}}</ref> calling for a shake up at the then fledgling Internet company.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB116382323602227236 | title = As Yahoo Falters, Executive's Memo Calls for Overhaul ' | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Kevin J. | last=Delaney | date=November 18, 2006}}</ref>\n\nGarlinghouse also had stints at [[Silver Lake Partners]], [[@Ventures]], [[@Home Network]], [[SBC Communications]] and was CEO of [[Dialpad]] Communications. He is an active [[angel investor]] in over 40 companies including hardware company [[Pure Storage]], AI startup [[Diffbot]], and [[Indigo Agriculture]].<ref>Brad Garlinghouse AngelList https://angel.co/brad-garlinghouse</ref> He is a board member at Animoto,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2012/04/10/animoto-brad-garlinghouse/|title=Now At 4M Users, Video Startup Animoto Adds Former Aol/Yahoo Exec Brad Garlinghouse To Board|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> and OutMatch.  He previously held board positions at [[Ancestry.com]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.com/corporate/about-ancestry/our-story|title=Our Story {{!}} Ancestry Corporate|website=www.ancestry.com|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> and Tonic Health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/tonic-health|title=Tonic Health|website=Crunchbase|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nGarlinghouse has a BA in economics from the [[University of Kansas]] and an MBA from [[Harvard Business School]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2018 Garlinghouse claimed on multiple occasions that by end of that year years, \"major banks\" would be using Ripple tools that made use of the the XRP cryptocurrency and that by end of 2019 \"dozens\" of banks would be using XRP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/video/2018/06/04/ripple-ceo-expect-dozens-of-banks-to-use-our-cryptocurrency-next-year.html|title=Ripple CEO: Expect dozens of banks to use our cryptocurrency next year|date=2018-06-04|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>  Both claims by the end of 2019 were proven to be untrue. In 2018 and 2019 Garlinghouse claimed on multiple occasions that the published error rate for SWIFT messaging was at least 6%<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snb.ch/en/ifor/research/id/researchtv-event?event=luUj6_tSzXh1s1Uf7RR88g|title=Swiss National Bank (SNB) - Research TV|website=www.snb.ch|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> , this was shown to be untrue by research published by the London School of Economics Business Review that showed Garlinghouse's claims were based on mis-reading of a paper published by SWIFT  that did not refer to error rates in messaging<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/businessreview/2019/11/04/do-six-per-cent-of-financial-transactions-sent-via-the-swift-system-really-fail/|title=Do six per cent of financial transactions sent via the Swift system really fail?|last=November 4th|last2=2019{{!}}Finance|date=2019-11-04|website=LSE Business Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25|last3=FinTech|last4=Information|last5=Technology|last6=Comments|first6=LSE alumni{{!}}3}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2020 an article in Financial Time Alphaville<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2020/02/26/1582730287000/The-art-of-redefining-success--MoneyGram-and-Ripple-edition/|website=ftalphaville.ft.com|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> revealed that Moneygram, the largest public user of Ripple's XRP based based liquidity tools has not only received a $50m investment prior to adopting the tools but that the software was provided free of charge by Ripple and that Moneygram was receiving an on-going subsidy for using XRP, amounting to $8.9m in Q4 2019. The same article revealed that Ripple was dependent on sales of XRP to remain profitable.\n\n\n==References==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100808193947/http://corp.aol.com/2010/05/12/brad-garlinghouse2 Brad Garlinghouse - AOL Corp]\n* [https://techcrunch.com/2012/05/15/brad-garlinghouse-becomes-ceo-of-booming-file-sharing-site-yousendit/ Garlinghouse new CEO of YouSendIt]\n*[http://recode.net/2014/09/12/why-brad-garlinghouse-left-hightail/ Why Brad Garlinghouse left Hightail]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garlinghouse, Brad}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n[[Category:American chief operating officers]]\n[[Category:Angel investors]]\n[[